mily Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Arnott  .","German: variant of   Arnold  . This surname is very rare in Germany. In North America, it may also be an altered form of the variant <b>Arnodt</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Arnott","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from a place called Arnot in Portmoak, Kinross.","Scottish and English: variant of   Arnold  .","English: variant of   Arnett  ."]},{"name":"Jarnot","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse.","Polish: from the personal name <i>Jarnot</i>, an adaptation of German   Arnot  . It occurs mainly in western part of Greater Poland and on the borderland of Silesia and Lesser Poland (the areas of old German settlement in Poland).","French: variant of   Garneau  ."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth Arnot was born in 1410, in Garlieston, Wigtownshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. She married William Stewart 2nd Laird of Dalswinton, Garlies and Minto about 1440. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in January 1459, in Wigtownshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 49, and was buried in Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1410–January 1459":"1410–jaanuar 1459","1408–1479":"1408–1479","1443–1500":"1443–1500","1445–1500":"1445–1500","1448–Male":"1448–Surnud","1450–1490":"1450–1490","1410–1459":"1410–1459","1450":"1450","1490":"1490","est 1448":"umbes 1448","1459":"1459","1448":"1448","1479":"1479","1445":"1445","1500":"1500","1410":"1410","1443":"1443","about 1445":"umbes 1445","about 1440":"umbes 1440","1408":"1408","January 1459":"jaanuar 1459","Garlieston, Wigtownshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Garlieston, Wigtownshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Galloway, Wigtownshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Wigtownshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Midlothia, Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Wigtownshire, Scotland":"Wigtownshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Garlieston, Wigtownshire, Scotland":"Garlieston, Wigtownshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1410–January 1459":"1410–tammikuu 1459","1408–1479":"1408–1479","1443–1500":"1443–1500","1445–1500":"1445–1500","1448–Male":"1448–Kuollut","1450–1490":"1450–1490","1410–1459":"1410–1459","1450":"1450","1490":"1490","est 1448":"noin 1448","1459":"1459","1448":"1448","1479":"1479","1445":"1445","1500":"1500","1410":"1410","1443":"1443","about 1445":"noin 1445","about 1440":"noin 1440","1408":"1408","January 1459":"tammikuu 1459","Garlieston, Wigtownshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Garlieston, Wigtownshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Galloway, Wigtownshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Wigtownshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Midlothia, Scotland":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta",